  ('Furnished', 'Negotiable', 'en', 'Negotiable', 'The property may be furnished or left unfurnished at the lessor''s request. Contact the listing agent/office to discuss options and cost differences.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Furnished/Negotiable/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Furnished', 'Partially', 'en', 'Partially', 'The dwelling being leased is partially furnished.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Furnished/Partially/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Furnished', 'Unfurnished', 'en', 'Unfurnished', 'The dwelling being leased is not furnished.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Furnished/Unfurnished/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Certified Passive House', 'en', 'Certified Passive House', 'Super-insulated new homes that have been built to meet certification requirements demonstrating minimal or no heating and cooling system.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Certified Passive House/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'ENERGY STAR Certified Homes', 'en', 'ENERGY STAR Certified Homes', 'EPA ENERGY STAR Certified Homes is a set of optional construction practices and technologies (above minimum code requirements) that builders can follow to upgrade a new home''s energy efficiency beyond minimum code requirements. Guidelines are outlined in the "National Performance Path" or "National Prescriptive Path." This whole-house label differs from the ENERGY STAR products label. To achieve the ENERGY STAR Certified Homes label, a home''s energy efficiency must be verified by a third-party organization.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/ENERGY STAR Certified Homes/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'EnerPHit', 'en', 'Ener PHit', 'Super-insulated existing homes that have been remodeled to meet certification requirements demonstrating minimal or no heating and cooling system.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/EnerPHit/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'HERS Index Score', 'en', 'HERS Index Score', 'The HERS Index is a nationally recognized scoring system for measuring a home''s energy performance in the U.S. To calculate a home''s HERS Index Score, a certified Residential Energy Services Network (RESNET) home energy rater will do a rating and compare the data against a reference home (a design-modeled home of the same size and shape as the actual home), so the HERS Index Score is always relative to the size shape, and type of the house. The lower the number, the more energy efficient the home.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/HERS Index Score/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Home Energy Score', 'en', 'Home Energy Score', 'The Home Energy Score, managed by the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE), is a national system that allows homes to receive an energy efficiency rating, similar to the miles per gallon (MPG) rating available for cars. The Home Energy Score uses a 10-point scale to reflect how much energy a home is expected to use under standard operating conditions. Homes that are expected to use the least amount of energy (and are considered the most energy efficient) score a 10, and homes that are expected to use the most amount of energy (and are considered the least energy efficient) score a 1. The Home Energy Score uses a standard calculation method and takes into account the home''s structure and envelope (walls, windows, foundation) and its heating, cooling and hot water systems. Only Qualified Assessors who pass a DOE exam are allowed to provide the Home Energy Score.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Home Energy Score/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Home Energy Upgrade Certificate of Energy Efficiency Improvements', 'en', 'Home Energy Upgrade Certificate of Energy Efficiency Improvements', 'Buildings Performance Institute BPI-2101-S-2013 Standard Requirements for a Certificate of Completion for Residential Energy Efficiency Upgrades specifies a standard way of describing the improvements made to an existing home through a home energy upgrade (HEU). Certificates are provided by a local energy efficiency program sponsor.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Home Energy Upgrade Certificate of Energy Efficiency Improvements/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Home Energy Upgrade Certificate of Energy Efficiency Performance', 'en', 'Home Energy Upgrade Certificate of Energy Efficiency Performance', 'Buildings Performance Institute BPI-2101-S-2013 Standard Requirements for a Certificate of Completion for Residential Energy Efficiency Upgrades specifies a standard way of describing the improvements made to an existing home through a home energy upgrade (HEU) and provides one or more measures of a home''s performance. Measures of performance may include a Home Energy Rating System (HERS) rating, a Home Energy Score, an indication of projected or actual energy consumption, or other systems. Certificates are provided by a local energy efficiency program sponsor.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Home Energy Upgrade Certificate of Energy Efficiency Performance/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Home Performance with ENERGY STAR', 'en', 'Home Performance with ENERGY STAR', 'Home Performance with ENERGY STAR (HPwES) offers whole-house solutions to high energy bills and homes with comfort problems. The program is managed by a local sponsor that recruits home improvement contractors who are qualified to perform comprehensive home assessments and improvements. Local sponsors must follow specific guidelines to participate as outlined in the HPwES Sponsor Guide and Reference Manual.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Home Performance with ENERGY STAR/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Indoor airPLUS', 'en', 'Indoor air PLUS', 'Indoor airPLUS from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) is a voluntary partnership and labeling program covering construction practices and technologies that builders can follow to reduce indoor air pollutants and improve the indoor air quality in a new home beyond minimum code requirements. It is only available to homes that first meet ENERGY STAR Certified Homes certification.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Indoor airPLUS/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'LEED For Homes', 'en', 'LEED For Homes', 'The U.S. Green Building Council (USGBC) residential rating system, LEED for Homes, was launched in 2008. The LEED rating systems are developed through an open, consensus-based process led by LEED committees. LEED is a voluntary program that provides independent, third-party verification that a home was designed and built using methods for achieving high performance in multiple areas of sustainability, including energy, water, waste management, indoor air quality and sustainable site development. There are multiple rating systems for all types of buildings, including existing buildings and homes for residential projects. Homes may achieve different levels of certification (platinum, gold, silver, certified) depending on the number of LEED prerequisites and credits that are met.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/LEED For Homes/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Living Building Challenge', 'en', 'Living Building Challenge', 'The International Living Future Institute third-party certification that proves that a home produces as much or more energy than is used.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Living Building Challenge/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'NGBS New Construction', 'en', 'NGBS New Construction', 'Home Innovation Research Labs certifies homes to the ICC-700 National Green Building Standard (NGBS), which has undergone the full consensus process and received approval from the American National Standards Institute (ANSI). Home Innovation Research Labs provides project certification to the NGBS. NGBS applies to both single-family homes and multifamily buildings. Certification options also exist for new construction, remodel projects (both whole-home and functional areas such as a kitchen or bathroom) and land development/subdivision. Homes may qualify for a bronze, silver, gold or emerald certification level depending on the number of green building practices met.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/NGBS New Construction/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'NGBS Small Projects Remodel', 'en', 'NGBS Small Projects Remodel', 'Home Innovation Research Labs provides project certification to the National Green Building Standard (NGBS). NGBS applies to both single-family homes and multifamily buildings. Certification options also exist for new construction, remodel projects (both whole-home and functional areas such as a kitchen or bathroom), and land development/subdivision. For the Small Projects Remodel, the functional area (kitchen, bathroom, basement, addition) is either certified or not. Unlike other NGBS certifications, multiple certification levels (bronze, silver, gold or emerald) do not exist for this certification option.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/NGBS Small Projects Remodel/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'NGBS Whole-Home Remodel', 'en', 'NGBS Whole-Home Remodel', 'Home Innovation Research Labs provides project certification to the National Green Building Standard (NGBS). NGBS applies to both single-family homes and multifamily buildings. Certification options also exist for new construction, remodel projects (both whole-home and functional areas such as a kitchen or bathroom), and land development/subdivision. Homes may qualify for a bronze, silver, gold or emerald certification level depending on the number of green building practices met.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/NGBS Whole-Home Remodel/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'PHIUS+', 'en', 'PHIUS+', 'Super-insulated homes that have met certification requirements demonstrating minimal or no heating and cooling system.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/PHIUS+/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Pearl Certification', 'en', 'Pearl Certification', 'Pearl is a national firm that provides third-party certification of high-performing homes (residential, 1-4 units) at various levels. For more information, visit https://pearlcertification.com/.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Pearl Certification/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'WaterSense', 'en', 'Water Sense', 'EPA WaterSense is a set of optional construction practices and technologies (above minimum code requirements) that builders can follow to ensure a home uses less water while still providing the same level of comfort and convenience. WaterSense also applies to specific plumbing fixtures (see InteriorFeatures) and should not be confused with the whole-house label.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/WaterSense/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenBuildingVerificationType', 'Zero Energy Ready Home', 'en', 'Zero Energy Ready Home', 'DOE Zero Energy Ready Home is a set of optional construction practices and technologies (above minimum code and ENERGY STAR Certified Home requirements) that builders can follow to ensure high-performance homes that are so energy efficient that all or most annual energy consumption can be offset with renewable energy. Guidelines are outlined in the "DOE Zero Energy Ready Home National Program Requirements."', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenBuildingVerificationType/Zero Energy Ready Home/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Appliances', 'en', 'Appliances', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has appliances that have some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Appliances/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Construction', 'en', 'Construction', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has construction that has some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Construction/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Doors', 'en', 'Doors', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has doors that have some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Doors/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Exposure/Shade', 'en', 'Exposure/Shade', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has exposure/shade that has some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Exposure%2FShade/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'HVAC', 'en', 'HVAC', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has a heating, ventilation and air conditioning system that has some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/HVAC/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Incentives', 'en', 'Incentives', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has incentives that have some green/efficiency focus.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Incentives/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Insulation', 'en', 'Insulation', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has insulation that has some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Insulation/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Lighting', 'en', 'Lighting', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has lighting that has some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Lighting/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Roof', 'en', 'Roof', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has a roof that has some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Roof/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Thermostat', 'en', 'Thermostat', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has a thermostat or thermostats that have some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Thermostat/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Water Heater', 'en', 'Water Heater', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has a water heater that has some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Water Heater/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyEfficient', 'Windows', 'en', 'Windows', 'For purposes of marketing, the property has windows that have some green/efficient rating or quality.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyEfficient/Windows/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyGeneration', 'Solar', 'en', 'Solar', 'A renewable form of onsite power generation. Most common are solar photovoltaic (PV) devices that generate electricity directly from sunlight via an electronic process that occurs naturally in certain types of material called semiconductors which power electrical devices or send electricity to the grid. http://www.seia.org/policy/solar-technology/photovoltaic-solar-electric', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyGeneration/Solar/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenEnergyGeneration', 'Wind', 'en', 'Wind', 'A renewable form of onsite power generation. Wind turbines use wind to make electricity and power electrical devices or send electricity to the grid. http://energy.gov/eere/wind/how-do-wind-turbines-work', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenEnergyGeneration/Wind/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenIndoorAirQuality', 'Contaminant Control', 'en', 'Contaminant Control', 'The property has been carefully designed to prevent, monitor and suppress pollution issues. Carefully selected low-emission materials have been used in the home and may include passive or active radon control, carbon monoxide monitoring and high-efficiency sealed combustion for equipment such as furnaces and water heaters. May include elimination of materials that contain lead or asbestos. May include reduction of materials that contain volatile organic compounds (VOCs, including formaldehyde) and pesticides.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenIndoorAirQuality/Contaminant Control/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenIndoorAirQuality', 'Integrated Pest Management', 'en', 'Integrated Pest Management', 'The property is designed for systematic management of pests that uses prevention, exclusion, monitoring and suppression.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenIndoorAirQuality/Integrated Pest Management/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenIndoorAirQuality', 'Moisture Control', 'en', 'Moisture Control', 'Every foundation, roof, roofing component, exterior wall, door, skylight and window is designed and maintained to be watertight and free of persistent dampness or moisture.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenIndoorAirQuality/Moisture Control/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenIndoorAirQuality', 'Ventilation', 'en', 'Ventilation', 'Furnaces, water heaters, woodstoves and other devices that employ combustion-burning fuel are vented to the outside in a manner that meets manufacturer specifications to prevent back drafting. Natural and/or mechanical ventilation delivers fresh air to every habitable room and bathroom to remove moisture-laden air and other contaminants generated during cooking and bathing/showering. The air exhausted from a bathroom, toilet room or kitchen does not vent into habitable space or an attic.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenIndoorAirQuality/Ventilation/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenSustainability', 'Conserving Methods', 'en', 'Conserving Methods', 'Construction is planned to require fewer materials while maintaining structural integrity and may include advanced wall framing as documented in several major green building programs. It may also include indigenous construction methods such as straw bale, sod, clay, etc., based on local climate, materials and practices.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenSustainability/Conserving Methods/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenSustainability', 'Onsite Recycling Center', 'en', 'Onsite Recycling Center', 'Property includes sufficient built-in storage space and/or containers for temporary storage of recyclable materials and/or compost collection.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenSustainability/Onsite Recycling Center/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenSustainability', 'Recyclable Materials', 'en', 'Recyclable Materials', 'The structure includes multiple products that have a significant amount of postconsumer recycled content. Major green building programs tend to use 25 percent postconsumer recycled content as a threshold. Postindustrial recycled content tends to count toward overall content but to a lesser scale. Some more common examples of recycled content materials include masonry, paving stones or foundations with fly ash; aluminum gutters and downspouts; decking; drywall fibers, insulation and house wrap; vinyl plastics; countertops; and cabinets, interior doors or trim. More details are available on the Home Innovation Research Labs “Browse Green Certified Products” tool or on the LEED Environmentally Preferred Products credit table.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenSustainability/Recyclable Materials/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenSustainability', 'Recycled Materials', 'en', 'Recycled Materials', 'The structure includes multiple products that have a significant amount of postconsumer recycled content. Major green building programs tend to use 25 percent postconsumer recycled content as a threshold. Postindustrial recycled content tends to count toward overall content but to a lesser scale. Some more common examples of recycled content materials include masonry, paving stones or foundations with fly ash; aluminum gutters and downspouts; decking; drywall fibers, insulation and house wrap; vinyl plastics; countertops; and cabinets, interior doors or trim. More details are available on the Home Innovation Research Labs “Browse Green Certified Products” tool or on the LEED Environmentally Preferred Products credit table.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenSustainability/Recycled Materials/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenSustainability', 'Regionally-Sourced Materials', 'en', 'Regionally-Sourced Materials', 'Refers to building materials that were manufactured, extracted, harvested or recovered within 500 miles of the building. Several major green building programs define regionally sourced as within a 500-mile radius.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenSustainability/Regionally-Sourced Materials/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenSustainability', 'Renewable Materials', 'en', 'Renewable Materials', 'The structure includes materials that are naturally occurring, abundant and/or fast growing. Some products are certified to come from fast-growing or otherwise renewable sources such as flooring and wood products. Some materials may be bio-based, which means they have been processed from once-living materials such as paper, straw, soy, natural fibers and crops.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenSustainability/Renewable Materials/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenSustainability', 'Salvaged Materials', 'en', 'Salvaged Materials', 'The structure incorporates materials that were diverted from a landfill and/or sourced to give an otherwise unused item fresh use as an attached fixture. May include bricks, timbers, roofing, flooring, walls, cabinets, doors, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenSustainability/Salvaged Materials/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Administrator', 'en', 'Administrator', 'An administrator such as a utility, governmental entity, etc. provided data such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Administrator/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Assessor', 'en', 'Assessor', 'The assessor provided data such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Assessor/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Builder', 'en', 'Builder', 'The builder provided data such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Builder/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Contractor or Installer', 'en', 'Contractor or Installer', 'The contractor or installer provided data such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Contractor or Installer/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Other', 'en', 'Other', 'Data such as photovoltaic characteristics, or a verified score, certification, label, etc. was received from another party not listed.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Other/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Owner', 'en', 'Owner', 'The owner provided data such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Owner/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Program Sponsor', 'en', 'Program Sponsor', 'The program sponsor provided data such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Program Sponsor/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Program Verifier', 'en', 'Program Verifier', 'The program verifier hired as a third-party provided data such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Program Verifier/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'Public Records', 'en', 'Public Records', 'Data such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc. was received from public records, such as a building permit.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/Public Records/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationSource', 'See Remarks', 'en', 'See Remarks', 'See remarks for information about the source of data, such as photovoltaic characteristics or a verified score, certification, label, etc.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationSource/See Remarks/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationStatus', 'Complete', 'en', 'Complete', 'Indicates that the verification process is complete. All requirements are complete and official verification documentation is on file or published; more than 12 months of occupancy.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationStatus/Complete/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenVerificationStatus', 'In Process', 'en', 'In Process', 'Indicates that the verification process is underway but not complete. Application, plans testing or specifications are in process; may be less than 12 months of occupancy.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenVerificationStatus/In Process/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenWaterConservation', 'Efficient Hot Water Distribution', 'en', 'Efficient Hot Water Distribution', 'Efficient hot water distribution systems are designed to generate hot water using fewer fuel resources and to get hot water to low-flow faucets and fixtures more quickly. These systems often feature carefully designed plumbing lines that are less redundant and/or shorter. Rather than measuring time to hot water at a fixture in gallons, efficient distribution systems can be measured in cups. The Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) WaterSense Guide for Hot Water Distribution and several green building programs have further details. This may also be known as structured plumbing.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenWaterConservation/Efficient Hot Water Distribution/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenWaterConservation', 'Gray Water System', 'en', 'Gray Water System', 'The property includes a gray water system.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenWaterConservation/Gray Water System/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenWaterConservation', 'Green Infrastructure', 'en', 'Green Infrastructure', 'A set of strategies and specifically designed systems to manage stormwater runoff through a variety of small, cost-effective landscape features located on a property. Green infrastructure employs infiltration (allowing water to slowly sink into the soil), evaporation/transpiration using native vegetation and rainwater capture and reuse (storing runoff to water plants, flush toilets, etc.). This may include green roof, rain gardens, rain barrels, permeable paving, etc. The Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Green Infrastructure website has more information at https://www.epa.gov/green-infrastructure.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenWaterConservation/Green Infrastructure/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenWaterConservation', 'Low-Flow Fixtures', 'en', 'Low-Flow Fixtures', 'Toilets, bathroom faucets, showerheads, irrigation controllers and other products can be manufactured to use less water than minimum standards. Some products are qualified by third-party programs like the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) WaterSense and are typically at least 20 percent more water-efficient than standard products. The EPA WaterSense website has additional information at https://www.epa.gov/watersense.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenWaterConservation/Low-Flow Fixtures/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenWaterConservation', 'Water Recycling', 'en', 'Water Recycling', 'The property includes a system to reuse stormwater via rain barrels or cisterns for landscaping or to treat and reuse water from bathroom sinks, showers and clothes washing drains for landscape irrigation and/or toilet flushing.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenWaterConservation/Water Recycling/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('GreenWaterConservation', 'Water-Smart Landscaping', 'en', 'Water-Smart Landscaping', 'Water-smart landscapes are designed to require less water and fertilizer treatments. These landscapes feature regionally appropriate plants that require low water and are native to the local climate. Plants are organized by hydrozones (watering needs). Any irrigation system is qualified for high water efficiency. Turfgrass is minimized and grown to the tallest height recommended. Strategic maintenance includes mulching and soil aeration. Other details are documented in Environmental Protection Agency''s Water-Smart Landscape Design Tips. https://www.epa.gov/watersense/landscaping-tips', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/GreenWaterConservation/Water-Smart Landscaping/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Active Solar', 'en', 'Active Solar', 'Active solar heating systems use solar energy to heat a fluid - either liquid or air - and then transfer the solar heat directly to the interior space or to a storage system for later use.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Active Solar/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Baseboard', 'en', 'Baseboard', 'Baseboard heating utilizes convection; as cold air drops from the window, it enters the baseboard heating unit where the air is warmed by heating elements, typically fins.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Baseboard/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Ceiling', 'en', 'Ceiling', 'A heating unit that is installed into or upon the surface of the ceiling.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Ceiling/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Central', 'en', 'Central', 'A system where heat is generated in one or more locations in the structure and distributed throughout the structure. The term "central" is commonly understood as distribution done by ducting air. Piping a fluid to radiators is also a central type of heating, but this can be clarified with the options "radiator" and "forced air."', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Central/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Coal', 'en', 'Coal', 'The heating system uses coal as its fuel to generate heat.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Coal/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Coal Stove', 'en', 'Coal Stove', 'A coal-burning stove that is used for heat.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Coal Stove/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Ductless', 'en', 'Ductless', 'The heating system does not have ducting like that found in forced-air systems.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Ductless/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'ENERGY STAR Qualified Equipment', 'en', 'ENERGY STAR Qualified Equipment', 'The heating system is ENERGY STAR qualified. Specific performance information must be determined by review of the actual unit.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/ENERGY STAR Qualified Equipment/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'ENERGY STAR/ACCA RSI Qualified Installation', 'en', 'ENERGY STAR/ACCA RSI Qualified Installation', 'The heating system installation was done by a qualified ENERGY STAR or ACCA RSI contractor.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/ENERGY STAR%2FACCA RSI Qualified Installation/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Electric', 'en', 'Electric', 'The heating system utilizes electricity and heating elements such as coils or fins to generate heat.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Electric/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Exhaust Fan', 'en', 'Exhaust Fan', 'The property has an exhaust fan.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Exhaust Fan/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Fireplace Insert', 'en', 'Fireplace Insert', 'The property has a fireplace insert for generating heat.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Fireplace Insert/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Fireplace(s)', 'en', 'Fireplace(s)', 'The property has one or more fireplaces used to generate heat.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Fireplace(s)/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Floor Furnace', 'en', 'Floor Furnace', 'The property has a radiant heating system that is mounted into the floor and distributes heat via convection.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Floor Furnace/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Forced Air', 'en', 'Forced Air', 'The property has a forced air system, typically via ducting throughout the structure.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Forced Air/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Geothermal', 'en', 'Geothermal', 'A geothermal heating system, also known as a ground source heat pump, transfers heat from below ground into the structure.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Geothermal/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Gravity', 'en', 'Gravity', 'A gravity heating system, also known as an octopus furnace, is typically a ducted system that doesn''t use a fan but rather is designed to allow the heat to rise naturally through the ducts to different areas of the structure.', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Gravity/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
  ('Heating', 'Heat Pump', 'en', 'Heat Pump', 'A system that exchanges heat between a warm and cool space. The heat exchange is done between the dwelling and another air space, like outdoors, or a water source or below ground (geothermal).', 'https://dd.reso.org/DD2.0/lookups/Heating/Heat Pump/', '2.0', 'reso_official_csv'),
